---
import GuideLayout from "../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  mainEntity: [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "What is a good GPA?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "A good GPA depends on your goals, but in general a 3.0 is solid, a 3.5 is strong, and a 4.0 is excellent."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "Is a 3.0 GPA good?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "Yes. A 3.0 GPA is generally considered good and shows consistent B-level work."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      name: "Is a 3.5 GPA good for college?",
      acceptedAnswer: {
        "@type": "Answer",
        text: "Yes. A 3.5 GPA is strong for many colleges and often puts students in a competitive position."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<GuideLayout
  title="What Is a Good GPA? (High School and College Guide)"
  description="What is a good GPA? Learn what GPA ranges mean, what colleges look for, and how to improve your GPA."
  slug="/what-is-a-good-gpa"
  heroTitle="What Is a Good GPA?"
  heroText="A good GPA depends on your goals, but some GPA ranges are clearly stronger than others. Here’s what different GPAs usually mean."
  faqSchema={faqSchema}
>
  <div class="card">
    <p>
      <strong>Short answer:</strong> a good GPA is usually
      <strong> 3.0 or higher</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
      If your GPA is around <strong>3.5 or above</strong>, that is considered
      strong. If it is near <strong>4.0</strong>, that is excellent.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Quick GPA Breakdown</h2>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>4.0 GPA:</strong> Excellent</li>
      <li><strong>3.5 GPA:</strong> Strong</li>
      <li><strong>3.0 GPA:</strong> Good</li>
      <li><strong>2.5 GPA:</strong> Average to below average</li>
      <li><strong>2.0 GPA:</strong> Passing, but limited</li>
      <li><strong>Below 2.0:</strong> Risk zone</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      These ranges are not official everywhere, but they are a useful guide for
      understanding where you stand.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>What Is a Good GPA in High School?</h2>

    <p>
      In high school, a good GPA usually means you are doing steady work across
      all your classes and keeping college options open.
    </p>

    <p>
      A <strong>3.0 GPA</strong> is a solid benchmark. A
      <strong> 3.5 GPA</strong> is better, and anything close to
      <strong> 4.0</strong> is very strong.
    </p>

    <p>
      If your school uses weighted GPA, your number may look higher because AP
      and Honors classes add extra points.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>What Is a Good GPA for College Admissions?</h2>

    <p>
      Colleges do not all expect the same GPA. More selective colleges usually
      want stronger grades, while many good schools accept students with a wider
      range.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>2.5–3.0:</strong> may work for some colleges</li>
      <li><strong>3.0–3.5:</strong> solid for many schools</li>
      <li><strong>3.5+:</strong> competitive for a lot of colleges</li>
      <li><strong>3.8+:</strong> very strong for selective schools</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      GPA is not the only factor, but it is one of the biggest.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Weighted vs. Unweighted GPA</h2>

    <p>
      A lot of students get confused here.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Unweighted GPA</strong> usually stays on a 4.0 scale
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Weighted GPA</strong> gives extra value to harder classes
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      That means a weighted GPA may be above 4.0, depending on your school’s
      system.
    </p>

    <p>
      You can estimate both here:
      <a href="/gpa-calculator/">GPA Calculator</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Is a 3.0 GPA Good?</h2>

    <p>
      Yes. A 3.0 GPA is generally considered good. It usually means you are
      earning mostly B’s.
    </p>

    <p>
      It may not be elite, but it is a solid GPA and keeps many options open.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Is a 3.5 GPA Good?</h2>

    <p>
      Yes. A 3.5 GPA is strong and often makes you competitive for many colleges,
      scholarships, and academic opportunities.
    </p>

    <p>
      A 3.5 usually means you are earning a mix of A’s and B’s, with more A-level
      work than the average student.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>How to Improve Your GPA</h2>

    <ol>
      <li>Raise low grades first</li>
      <li>Complete missing assignments</li>
      <li>Improve test and quiz scores</li>
      <li>Use remaining assignments wisely</li>
      <li>Track where you stand regularly</li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      Helpful tools:
      <a href="/grade-calculator/">Grade Calculator</a>,
      <a href="/what-grade-do-i-need-calculator/"> What Grade Do I Need Calculator</a>,
      and
      <a href="/final-exam-calculator/"> Final Exam Calculator</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

    <p>
      A good GPA depends on your goals, but here’s the simplest way to think about it:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>3.0</strong> = good</li>
      <li><strong>3.5</strong> = strong</li>
      <li><strong>4.0</strong> = excellent</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      If your GPA is lower than you want, the good news is that you can improve
      it over time by raising your course grades and making smart decisions about
      remaining work.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>What is a good GPA?</h3>
      <p>
        A good GPA is usually 3.0 or higher, though stronger goals often mean
        aiming for 3.5 or above.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Is a 3.0 GPA good?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. A 3.0 GPA is generally considered good and reflects consistent B-level work.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Is a 3.5 GPA good for college?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. A 3.5 GPA is strong for many colleges and can make you competitive.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</GuideLayout>
